WEBVTT

1
00:03:09,252 --> 00:03:11,903
Judd, you can't.

2
00:03:11,972 --> 00:03:13,794
I got to
get in the house.

3
00:03:13,859 --> 00:03:17,154
Poke your head out in the
clear, and a Falin will get you.

4
00:03:18,211 --> 00:03:22,237
But Melissa,
she's going to have a baby.

5
00:03:40,803 --> 00:03:42,047
Hit you, David?

6
00:03:42,115 --> 00:03:43,937
No Falin can ever
get me, Uncle Judd.

7
00:04:11,044 --> 00:04:14,589
Oh, God, give her the
strength to be good,

8
00:04:16,259 --> 00:04:19,358
to be never hateful
and never fight.

9
00:04:21,763 --> 00:04:24,480
And don't let her
carry the burden of fear,

10
00:04:25,283 --> 00:04:29,277
watching her loved ones
and seeing them die.

11
00:04:31,107 --> 00:04:34,205
Always asking
out of her heart,

12
00:04:34,275 --> 00:04:40,385
" Why has it got to be?
Why has it got to be?"

13
00:05:04,707 --> 00:05:09,562
<i>When it's twilight
on the trail</i>

14
00:05:10,691 --> 00:05:13,725
<i>And I jog along</i>

15
00:05:13,796 --> 00:05:16,381
<i>The world is like a dream</i>

16
00:05:16,483 --> 00:05:21,698
<i>And the ripple of the stream
is my song</i>

17
00:05:22,403 --> 00:05:26,811
<i>When it's twilight
on the trail</i>

18
00:05:27,907 --> 00:05:31,103
<i>And I rest once more</i>

19
00:05:31,171 --> 00:05:33,560
<i>My ceiling is the sky</i>

20
00:05:33,635 --> 00:05:38,589
<i>And the grass on which I lie
is my floor</i>

21
00:05:40,131 --> 00:05:44,735
<i>Never ever have a nickel in my jeans</i>

22
00:05:45,699 --> 00:05:49,311
<i>Never ever
have a debt to pay</i>

23
00:05:50,947 --> 00:05:55,933
<i>Still I understand
what real contentment means</i>

24
00:05:56,867 --> 00:06:00,795
<i>Guess I was born that way</i>

25
00:06:02,467 --> 00:06:07,682
<i>When it's twilight
on the trail</i>

26
00:06:08,739 --> 00:06:12,449
<i>And my voice is still</i>

27
00:06:12,515 --> 00:06:15,810
<i>Please plant
this heart of mine</i>

28
00:06:15,875 --> 00:06:21,855
<i>Underneath the Lonesome Pine on the hill</i>

29
00:06:22,723 --> 00:06:24,545
And I says to him, I says,
"Look here, Zeke Denker,

30
00:06:24,611 --> 00:06:26,978
" you're driving your hogs
to mighty poor swill. "

31
00:06:27,043 --> 00:06:28,669
Bet that buttoned him.
Not Zeke.

32
00:06:28,739 --> 00:06:31,456
He's the laughingest man I
ever met. Nothing bites him.

33
00:06:31,523 --> 00:06:33,083
Laughs when it's clever enough to rain.

34
00:06:33,219 --> 00:06:34,780
Laughs when
the sun shines.

35
00:06:34,851 --> 00:06:37,502
He looks me
right in the eye...

36
00:06:37,924 --> 00:06:39,484
Dave's better.

37
00:06:39,555 --> 00:06:41,180
Is he?
Yep.

38
00:06:41,891 --> 00:06:45,186
Perking up a mite.
Arm's a little green

39
00:06:45,252 --> 00:06:47,291
but I stuck a chaw
of tobaccy on it.

40
00:06:47,363 --> 00:06:49,535
Cold rifle barreI
will do it more good.

41
00:06:49,603 --> 00:06:52,123
What he have to say?
About the Falins I mean.

42
00:06:52,195 --> 00:06:55,643
" Eat your sow belly and get
for home. " That's what he said.

43
00:06:55,715 --> 00:06:58,082
Said, " Ain't gonna be no
fighting till I can tote a gun. "

44
00:06:58,147 --> 00:06:59,227
And I come six miles.

45
00:06:59,300 --> 00:07:00,347
Six miles.

46
00:07:00,419 --> 00:07:02,623
I can throw a clump
of dogwood that far.

47
00:07:02,691 --> 00:07:05,560
I'm nigh on to 30 miles.
Look. Look.

48
00:07:06,723 --> 00:07:08,666
Gather around now.
Gather around.

49
00:07:08,739 --> 00:07:10,649
I'm really going to
show you something now.

50
00:07:10,723 --> 00:07:13,210
Maybe we's will
get a go at the kid.

51
00:07:13,283 --> 00:07:17,178
Whenever Judd Tolliver gets
an itch to plug the Falins,

52
00:07:17,251 --> 00:07:19,739
he starts playing
with the young ones.

53
00:07:21,123 --> 00:07:23,393
I'm gonna be
the human hub.

54
00:07:23,459 --> 00:07:27,583
Now, Willie, you go down there and
stop me if I get to going too fast.

55
00:07:30,595 --> 00:07:33,562
Lizzie Bee, you better
go down and help Willie.

56
00:07:35,331 --> 00:07:38,200
Look out now, here I come.
Don't forget to stop me.

57
00:07:47,971 --> 00:07:50,142
Well, why didn't
you stop me?

58
00:07:58,307 --> 00:08:01,242
Judd's better than that
wagon show we saw once.

59
00:08:08,419 --> 00:08:11,103
Melissa, you got a
bellyache or something?

60
00:08:12,803 --> 00:08:14,494
Just thinking, Lina.

61
00:08:14,563 --> 00:08:16,189
Sakes and sassafras!

62
00:08:16,259 --> 00:08:17,982
Thinking
boils the pot over.

63
00:08:18,051 --> 00:08:21,434
It boils over and over and
over if you ain't thinking.

64
00:08:22,883 --> 00:08:26,396
Killing.
All the time killing.

65
00:08:26,467 --> 00:08:28,922
They are planning it now.
They done it yesterday,

66
00:08:28,995 --> 00:08:31,362
and the week before,
and the year before that.

67
00:08:31,427 --> 00:08:34,242
Ever since I was a
little child they done it.

68
00:08:34,307 --> 00:08:36,129
Kill a Falin.
Kill a Falin.

69
00:08:36,195 --> 00:08:37,788
That's all they could say.

70
00:08:37,859 --> 00:08:40,761
Plowing, splitting reins.
Filling the corn crib.

71
00:08:40,835 --> 00:08:44,992
Kill a Falin! And the echo comes
back to us from over the hills.

72
00:08:45,059 --> 00:08:49,314
Kill a Tolliver.
Kill. Kill. Why?

73
00:08:49,379 --> 00:08:50,524
Melissa!

74
00:08:56,387 --> 00:08:58,776
What you biting
your paws about, Auntie?

75
00:08:58,851 --> 00:09:01,501
Worrying, I guess, June
and Buddie ain't back yet.

76
00:09:01,571 --> 00:09:02,946
Where they be?

77
00:09:03,011 --> 00:09:06,077
Over at the yard doctor,
getting a potion for you.

78
00:09:10,819 --> 00:09:12,925
Is that the way
you like it?

79
00:09:16,226 --> 00:09:17,175
Just right.

80
00:09:17,251 --> 00:09:20,000
You should have let me
get a town doctor, Dave.

81
00:09:20,066 --> 00:09:23,165
It don't look right.
It's too swole up.

82
00:09:23,235 --> 00:09:24,479
You're awfully
good to me, Auntie.

83
00:09:24,547 --> 00:09:26,041
You're a good boy, Dave.

84
00:09:26,115 --> 00:09:27,457
Your boy.

85
00:09:27,523 --> 00:09:28,832
My boy.

86
00:09:28,899 --> 00:09:30,907
Sometimes I wished I was,
Auntie. Then I wished I wasn't

87
00:09:30,979 --> 00:09:34,395
'cause if I was, I couldn't
marry June and if I wasn't...

88
00:09:35,299 --> 00:09:37,787
Relations like we ones
got me all thicked up.

89
00:09:37,859 --> 00:09:40,280
Cousins are always thicker than
fleas in the mountains, Dave.

90
00:09:42,339 --> 00:09:44,379
I'm a big, big
black bear.

91
00:09:46,723 --> 00:09:48,610
I'm a mean black bear.

92
00:09:54,179 --> 00:09:57,342
I'm getting closer.
I'll get you.

93
00:10:04,931 --> 00:10:06,939
I'm coming closer.

94
00:10:21,123 --> 00:10:23,938
You laugh at me, foreigner,
and I'll... I'll...

95
00:10:24,291 --> 00:10:26,560
I don't blame you, I'd
do the same thing myself.

96
00:10:37,315 --> 00:10:39,704
That was funny.
Why didn't you laugh?

97
00:10:39,779 --> 00:10:40,957
She's one of
the Tollivers.

98
00:10:41,027 --> 00:10:42,139
That's still funny.

99
00:10:42,211 --> 00:10:43,226
She didn't think so.

100
00:10:43,299 --> 00:10:44,924
That's a woman's privilege.

101
00:10:44,995 --> 00:10:46,075
Now, where were we?

102
00:10:46,147 --> 00:10:47,424
Right in the middle of
that fault, over there.

103
00:10:47,491 --> 00:10:48,538
Yeah.

104
00:10:48,611 --> 00:10:51,480
Two years supply of strip-coaI
before we have to drift mine it.

105
00:10:51,555 --> 00:10:52,668
We'll steam-shovel
the top coal

106
00:10:52,739 --> 00:10:54,877
and make it pay for
the railroad up here.

107
00:10:54,947 --> 00:10:56,191
You haven't got it yet.

108
00:10:56,259 --> 00:10:57,274
No.

109
00:10:57,347 --> 00:10:58,754
Well, suppose you let
me worry about that.

110
00:10:58,819 --> 00:11:02,299
The right and title to that
privilege is yours, my friend.

111
00:11:03,011 --> 00:11:05,149
You got that privilege
this very minute.

112
00:11:05,219 --> 00:11:06,844
Start using it.

113
00:11:11,267 --> 00:11:12,674
I was just
running in that wood,

114
00:11:12,739 --> 00:11:14,365
and I heard
she was a bear.

115
00:11:14,499 --> 00:11:16,409
And when I looked
around to see if she

116
00:11:16,547 --> 00:11:18,008
was going to eat me,
she was gone.

117
00:11:18,083 --> 00:11:20,352
Maybe she ate herself
and disappeared.

118
00:11:20,419 --> 00:11:22,361
Judd Tolliver,
how you talk.

119
00:11:23,011 --> 00:11:25,793
Child. Child. You mustn't.

120
00:11:25,859 --> 00:11:27,485
Juny's coming back.

121
00:11:27,555 --> 00:11:29,976
Maybe she stopped
down by the river.

122
00:11:38,339 --> 00:11:40,510
Looks like she fetched
the river with her.

123
00:11:40,579 --> 00:11:41,757
June!

124
00:11:41,827 --> 00:11:43,136
Well, I brung it,
didn't I?

125
00:11:43,203 --> 00:11:44,992
June, if you ain't
the lookingest...

126
00:11:45,059 --> 00:11:46,269
I've been running
across that log

127
00:11:46,339 --> 00:11:48,379
ever since I was knee
high to a grasshopper.

128
00:11:48,451 --> 00:11:50,361
I can catch a squirreI
on it with one hand,

129
00:11:50,434 --> 00:11:51,841
but when that dog
see that foreigner...

130
00:11:51,906 --> 00:11:53,216
Foreigner?

131
00:11:53,475 --> 00:11:56,224
He stopped right smack-dab in the
middle of the log and I tripped.

132
00:11:56,291 --> 00:11:57,666
What was
the foreigner doing?

133
00:11:57,731 --> 00:11:59,771
Don't know.
Wasn't looking.

134
00:11:59,843 --> 00:12:02,177
Before you know it, there
I go. Plunk, right down.

135
00:12:02,243 --> 00:12:03,421
What did he look like?

136
00:12:03,491 --> 00:12:04,603
Just had a squint.

137
00:12:04,707 --> 00:12:09,017
He's about so tall,
about that wide.

138
00:12:09,091 --> 00:12:11,294
Was all dressed in brown,
even his hat.

139
00:12:11,363 --> 00:12:12,737
And his coat had a belt.

140
00:12:12,803 --> 00:12:14,047
Just a squint?

141
00:12:14,499 --> 00:12:15,840
Dave Tolliver,
if you're thinking

142
00:12:15,906 --> 00:12:17,216
what I'm a thinking, I'm
going to tell you off.

143
00:12:17,283 --> 00:12:19,868
Go down to the creek
and wash your dirty face.

144
00:12:19,939 --> 00:12:21,914
For two carrot seeds,
I'd rub it all over you.

145
00:12:21,987 --> 00:12:24,125
You do it, and I'll
spank you where it hurts.

146
00:12:24,194 --> 00:12:25,951
You will, will you?

147
00:12:29,186 --> 00:12:30,615
Did that hurt?

148
00:12:32,226 --> 00:12:33,633
How could it?

149
00:12:33,955 --> 00:12:35,515
Oh!

150
00:12:37,667 --> 00:12:39,489
I've been talking
to your pappy.

151
00:12:40,195 --> 00:12:41,984
We's going to get married.

152
00:12:43,939 --> 00:12:45,052
When?
Hog killing time.

153
00:12:45,123 --> 00:12:46,464
Your pappy has invited
all the Tollivers.

154
00:12:46,531 --> 00:12:48,702
The whole kit
and boodle of them.

155
00:12:48,771 --> 00:12:50,462
I ain't marrying
till green up.

156
00:12:50,531 --> 00:12:52,189
Spring's always
the time to do them things.

157
00:12:52,291 --> 00:12:54,298
Then it'll be next
green up and the next.

158
00:12:56,419 --> 00:12:58,208
I don't feeI nothing.

159
00:12:58,787 --> 00:13:01,024
Like... What do you mean?

160
00:13:02,499 --> 00:13:03,742
I don't know.

161
00:13:07,619 --> 00:13:10,008
Come on. Come on.

162
00:13:10,755 --> 00:13:12,064
Dinner.

163
00:13:12,131 --> 00:13:13,625
Come on.

164
00:13:15,011 --> 00:13:16,604
Better make it just a
dipping, June, or them

165
00:13:16,675 --> 00:13:18,879
hungry mouths
will eat that table bare.

166
00:13:18,947 --> 00:13:22,427
Ma. Come here.

167
00:13:24,579 --> 00:13:27,742
Ma. Do I...

168
00:13:28,803 --> 00:13:30,265
Do I like Dave?

169
00:13:30,882 --> 00:13:33,948
Why, honey,
I think you do.

170
00:13:34,722 --> 00:13:36,413
Like you like Pappy?

171
00:13:39,426 --> 00:13:44,828
Well, you remember when
Dave went to Pokey Wells,

172
00:13:45,763 --> 00:13:48,446
you was a-grieving for him
then, weren't you?

173
00:13:48,514 --> 00:13:52,159
And when he's to home, he
don't make no nevermind to you?

174
00:13:52,483 --> 00:13:54,141
- But, Ma...
- Melissa,

175
00:13:54,211 --> 00:13:55,902
the folks are waiting for their dinner.

176
00:13:55,971 --> 00:13:57,400
Coming.

177
00:13:57,827 --> 00:13:59,801
Well, that's
liking, honey.

178
00:15:15,491 --> 00:15:17,563
This here man wants
to talk to you, Judd.

179
00:15:17,635 --> 00:15:18,845
Does, huh?

180
00:15:18,914 --> 00:15:20,856
My name is Hale,
Jack Hale.

181
00:15:22,979 --> 00:15:25,019
I wonder if I could
see you alone.

182
00:15:25,091 --> 00:15:26,236
Here's all right.

183
00:15:26,307 --> 00:15:27,419
Well, I...

184
00:15:29,091 --> 00:15:31,905
You see, I wanted to
talk to you about coaI.

185
00:15:34,915 --> 00:15:36,857
The coaI on your property,
I mean.

186
00:15:37,602 --> 00:15:39,544
You know what I mean? The
fault down about a mile.

187
00:15:39,619 --> 00:15:42,336
Well, you've seen the coaI.
You know what I mean.

188
00:15:42,402 --> 00:15:45,785
The fault. The Alton people,
I'm with them and they...

189
00:15:47,651 --> 00:15:49,178
You was talking
about coaI.

190
00:15:49,251 --> 00:15:50,363
Oh, yes. CoaI.

191
00:15:50,434 --> 00:15:51,863
There'll be a railroad
up along the Ticopi

192
00:15:51,939 --> 00:15:53,499
and then down across
the ridge to your place.

193
00:15:53,570 --> 00:15:54,683
Who said there would?

194
00:15:54,755 --> 00:15:56,281
I mean, of course,
if it's agreeable with

195
00:15:56,354 --> 00:15:58,493
the contracting parties,
like yourself.

196
00:15:58,563 --> 00:16:00,505
The thing will make you rich.
There's no doubt about that.

197
00:16:00,579 --> 00:16:01,626
And if we can
make a deaI...

198
00:16:01,699 --> 00:16:03,106
Who's the others?

199
00:16:04,226 --> 00:16:06,201
The contract with you
is for the coaI.

200
00:16:06,275 --> 00:16:07,452
Who is the others?

201
00:16:07,522 --> 00:16:10,556
Well, there's severaI
other people, but mainly...

202
00:16:17,314 --> 00:16:18,263
How long have you had that?

203
00:16:18,338 --> 00:16:19,713
You ain't
answered me yet.

204
00:16:19,779 --> 00:16:21,470
When did this arm begin
to show that color?

205
00:16:21,570 --> 00:16:23,610
Three days ago now,
I think.

206
00:16:25,250 --> 00:16:27,803
Get me some
warm water, quick.

207
00:16:27,874 --> 00:16:29,303
It ain't bad, is it?

208
00:16:29,379 --> 00:16:31,713
Bad?
It's gangrenous infection.

209
00:16:31,778 --> 00:16:33,273
The flesh,
it's rotting, it's dying.

210
00:16:33,346 --> 00:16:34,524
You ain't no doctor.

211
00:16:34,594 --> 00:16:36,154
You wanna live,
don't you?

212
00:16:36,643 --> 00:16:38,465
Why didn't you get this
man to a doctor? Did.

213
00:16:38,531 --> 00:16:40,222
There it be. Snake brew.
You fooI.

214
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:42,680
He'll die if something isn't done.

215
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:45,244
Am I dying, Judd?

216
00:16:45,891 --> 00:16:47,549
Sure.

217
00:16:47,619 --> 00:16:50,040
Better start making
the pine box, I guess.

218
00:16:50,114 --> 00:16:53,660
That's just what you will be
doing if something isn't done.

219
00:16:55,874 --> 00:16:57,118
Now listen to me.

220
00:16:57,186 --> 00:16:59,074
Once an infection like
this sets in, it kills.

221
00:16:59,139 --> 00:17:01,954
The only possible cure is
to cut it out, and then pray.

222
00:17:02,019 --> 00:17:03,710
Now do you understand?

223
00:17:03,779 --> 00:17:06,200
No. No.
They don't understand.

224
00:17:06,274 --> 00:17:09,121
They don't understand nothing
but shooting and killing.

225
00:17:09,187 --> 00:17:10,943
That's all they understand.
Melissa.

226
00:17:11,011 --> 00:17:14,142
I been begging you to get a
doctor, but no, you got to plan.

227
00:17:14,210 --> 00:17:17,625
You got to scheme, you got to
figure out how to kill. All of you.

228
00:17:18,883 --> 00:17:22,112
Your crops could rot
and your cattle starve.

229
00:17:22,179 --> 00:17:24,830
And you wouldn't care as long as
you was back of a squirreI rifle,

230
00:17:24,899 --> 00:17:27,713
and here was a Falin
at the other end of it.

231
00:17:28,451 --> 00:17:31,964
Now it's getting back
at you. He's dying.

232
00:17:32,387 --> 00:17:36,380
You heard him say it.
My Davie's dying.

233
00:17:36,962 --> 00:17:38,140
Melissa.

234
00:17:46,146 --> 00:17:47,640
Here.

235
00:17:48,386 --> 00:17:49,369
I'm sorry,
I didn't know...

236
00:17:49,442 --> 00:17:51,035
Here.

237
00:17:53,347 --> 00:17:54,754
Get me a cloth,
a tourniquet.

238
00:17:54,819 --> 00:17:58,135
Something to tighten around his
arm and shut off the circulation.

239
00:18:00,067 --> 00:18:03,198
Get me some small knives,
the sharpest you've got.

240
00:18:03,586 --> 00:18:06,750
Get that fire going. Heat the
knives till they're white-hot.

241
00:18:08,674 --> 00:18:11,357
Keep that down and
help me steady his arm.

242
00:18:31,938 --> 00:18:33,629
This is going to hurt.
We have no anesthetic.

243
00:18:33,698 --> 00:18:36,219
Something to put you to sleep, I mean.

244
00:18:38,402 --> 00:18:41,370
Better stouting up the corn
liquor with a little pepper.

